**Beijing**, &#91;a&#93; [previously romanized](/Chinese_postal_romanization) as Peking, &#91;b&#93; is the [capital city](/Capital_city) of [China](/China). With a population exceeding 22 million, &#91;11&#93; it holds the distinction of being the world's [most populous national capital city](/List_of_national_capitals_by_population). It's also China's [second largest city by urban area](/List_of_cities_in_China_by_population), trailing only [Shanghai](/Shanghai). Situated in [Northern China](/North_China), Beijing functions as a [municipality](/Direct-administered_municipalities_of_China) directly administered by the [State Council](/Government_of_the_People%27s_Republic_of_China), encompassing [16 districts](/List_of_administrative_divisions_of_Beijing) that range from urban centers to suburban and rural expanses.&#160;Geographically, it's largely encircled by [Hebei Province](/Hebei_Province), with [Tianjin](/Tianjin) bordering it to the southeast. Together, these three administrative divisions form the significant [Jing-Jin-Ji cluster](/Jing-Jin-Ji).&#160;

Beijing stands as a [global city](/Global_city), recognized as one of the world's foremost centers for culture, diplomacy, [politics](/Politics_of_Beijing), [finance](/Global_Financial_Centres_Index), [business and economics](/Economy_of_Beijing), education, [research](/List_of_cities_by_scientific_output), [language](/Beijing_dialect), tourism, media, sports, [science and technology](/Science_and_technology_in_the_People%27s_Republic_of_China), [transportation](/Transport_in_China), and [art](/Art).&#160;It hosts the headquarters for the majority of [China's largest state-owned companies](/List_of_the_largest_companies_of_China) and boasts the highest number of Fortune Global 500 companies worldwide, alongside the four largest [financial institutions](/List_of_largest_banks) globally based on total assets.&#160;Furthermore, it's a crucial nexus for the [national highway](/China_National_Highways_of_Beijing), [expressway](/Expressways_of_Beijing), [railway](/Rail_transport_in_China), and [high-speed rail](/High-speed_rail_in_China) networks.&#160;For a decade preceding the [COVID-19 pandemic](/COVID-19_pandemic_in_China), [Beijing Capital International Airport](/Beijing_Capital_International_Airport) held the title of [Asia's busiest airport](/List_of_the_busiest_airports_in_Asia) (2009–2019) and the [second busiest in the world](/World%27s_busiest_airports_by_passenger_traffic) (2010–2019).&#160;In 2020, the [Beijing subway](/Beijing_Subway) ranked as the fourth busiest and second longest [metro system](/List_of_metro_systems) globally.&#160;The newer [Beijing Daxing International Airport](/Beijing_Daxing_International_Airport), Beijing's second international gateway, features the world's largest single-structure [airport terminal](/Airport_terminal).&#160;&#91;18&#93; &#91;19&#93; The city has been the venue for numerous significant international and national sporting events, most notably the [2008 Summer Olympics](/2008_Summer_Olympics) and the [2008 Summer Paralympics](/2008_Summer_Paralympics).&#160;In 2022, Beijing achieved a unique milestone by becoming the first city ever to host both the [Summer](/2008_Summer_Olympics) and [Winter Olympics](/2022_Winter_Olympics), and subsequently, both the [Summer](/2008_Summer_Paralympics) and [Winter Paralympics](/2022_Winter_Paralympics).&#160;&#91;20&#93; &#91;21&#93;

Beijing's architectural landscape is a fascinating blend of traditional Chinese design and contemporary styles.&#160;While one part of the city showcases its modernization and renovation, the other half still preserves its traditional [hutong](/Hutong) districts, offering a glimpse into the past.&#160;&#91;22&#93; As one of the world's most ancient continuously inhabited cities, with a recorded history stretching back over three millennia, Beijing has served as the political heart of China for the better part of the last eight centuries.&#160;&#91;23&#93; It was also the [largest city in the world by population](/List_of_largest_cities_throughout_history) for much of the [second millennium AD](/2nd_millennium).&#160;&#91;24&#93; Strategically positioned with mountains framing its inland location on three sides, and bolstered by its [ancient city fortifications](/Beijing_city_fortifications), Beijing was developed to serve as the imperial residence.&#160;The city is celebrated for its opulent palaces, temples, parks, gardens, tombs, and [walls and gates](/Beijing_city_fortifications).&#160;&#91;25&#93; Beijing is widely considered a premier global tourist destination, ranking second in tourist earnings worldwide in 2018, just behind [Shanghai](/Shanghai).&#160;&#91;26&#93; It is home to numerous national [monuments and museums](/List_of_museums_in_China) and boasts **eight** UNESCO [World Heritage Sites](/World_Heritage_Site): the [Forbidden City](/Forbidden_City), the [Temple of Heaven](/Temple_of_Heaven), the [Summer Palace](/Summer_Palace), the [Ming Tombs](/Ming_Tombs), the [Zhoukoudian Peking Man Site](/Zhoukoudian_Peking_Man_Site), the [Beijing Central Axis](/Beijing_Central_Axis), and significant portions of the [Great Wall](/Great_Wall) and the [Grand Canal](/Grand_Canal_(China)).&#160;These sites are major draws for tourists.&#160;&#91;27&#93; The city's traditional housing style, the [Siheyuans](/Siheyuan), and the narrow alleys connecting them, the [hutongs](/Hutong), are also popular attractions, particularly in the urban core.

Beijing's [public universities](/List_of_universities_and_colleges_in_Beijing) represent over a fifth of the [Double First-Class Construction](/Double_First-Class_Construction) universities in China.&#160;Many of these institutions consistently rank among the top universities in the Asia-Pacific and globally, including [Tsinghua University](/Tsinghua_University), [Peking University](/Peking_University), and [UCAS](/University_of_the_Chinese_Academy_of_Sciences).&#160;&#91;28&#93; &#91;29&#93; &#91;30&#93; The [Beijing CBD](/Beijing_CBD) is a hub for the city's economic growth, marked by the ongoing construction of numerous [skyscrapers](/List_of_tallest_buildings_in_Beijing).&#160;The [Zhongguancun](/Zhongguancun) area is a globally recognized center for scientific and technological innovation and entrepreneurship.&#160;Consistently since its inception in 2016, Beijing has led the world in scientific research output, according to the [Nature Index](/Nature_Index).&#160;&#91;34&#93; &#91;35&#93; Beijing hosts [176 foreign embassies](/List_of_diplomatic_missions_in_China) and serves as the headquarters for numerous organizations, including the [Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank](/Asian_Infrastructure_Investment_Bank) (AIIB), the [Shanghai Cooperation Organisation](/Shanghai_Cooperation_Organisation) (SCO), the [Silk Road Fund](/Silk_Road_Fund), the [Chinese Academy of Sciences](/Chinese_Academy_of_Sciences), the [Chinese Academy of Engineering](/Chinese_Academy_of_Engineering), the [Chinese Academy of Social Sciences](/Chinese_Academy_of_Social_Sciences), the [Central Academy of Fine Arts](/Central_Academy_of_Fine_Arts), the [Central Academy of Drama](/Central_Academy_of_Drama), the [Central Conservatory of Music](/Central_Conservatory_of_Music), and the [Red Cross Society of China](/Red_Cross_Society_of_China).

### Etymology

•
Main article: [Names of Beijing](/Names_of_Beijing)

Over its 3,000-year history, the city now known as Beijing has borne many names.&#160;The current name, Beijing, meaning "Northern Capital" (derived from the [Chinese characters](/Chinese_characters) 北 *běi* for north and 京 *jīng* for capital), was adopted in 1403 during the [Ming dynasty](/Ming_dynasty).&#160;This designation was intended to distinguish it from [Nanjing](/Nanjing), the "Southern Capital."&#160;&#91;36&#93; The English spelling "Beijing" reflects the government's official [romanization](/Romanization_of_China) system, implemented in the 1980s, based on the pronunciation of the characters in [Standard Mandarin](/Standard_Mandarin).&#160;An earlier English rendition, "Peking," was popularized by the Jesuit missionary [Martino Martini](/Martino_Martini) in a widely circulated atlas published in Amsterdam in 1655.&#160;&#91;37&#93; While "Peking" is no longer the standard name, remnants of this older romanization persist in some of the city's established locations and institutions, such as [Beijing Capital International Airport](/Beijing_Capital_International_Airport) (with the [IATA code](/International_Air_Transport_Association_code) PEK) and [Peking University](/Peking_University),&#160;&#91;39&#93; &#91;40&#93; which retain the historical spelling.

The single Chinese character abbreviation for Beijing is 京, commonly seen on vehicle license plates.&#160;The official Latin alphabet abbreviation designated by the [Standardization Administration of China](/Standardization_Administration_of_China) is "BJ".&#160;&#91;41&#93;

### History

•
Main article: [History of Beijing](/History_of_Beijing)

#### Early history

The earliest evidence of human habitation within the Beijing municipality was discovered in the caves of [Dragon Bone Hill](/Dragon_Bone_Hill), near the village of [Zhoukoudian](/Zhoukoudian) in [Fangshan District](/Fangshan_District).&#160;These caves were home to [Peking Man](/Peking_Man), an early hominin species whose fossils date back 230,000 to 250,000 years.&#160;Later, [Paleolithic](/Paleolithic) [Homo sapiens](/Homo_sapiens) also inhabited the area, approximately 27,000 years ago.&#160;Archaeological findings reveal numerous [Neolithic](/Neolithic) settlements scattered throughout the municipality, including one in the present-day central district of [Wangfujing](/Wangfujing).

The very first [walled city](/Ancient_Chinese_urban_planning) in what is now Beijing was [Jicheng](/Jicheng_(Beijing)), established in 1045 BC as the capital of the [state of Ji](/State_of_Ji).&#160;Within the boundaries of modern Beijing, Jicheng was situated near the area of [Guang'anmen](/Guang'anmen) in the southern part of [Xicheng District](/Xicheng_District).&#160;&#91;43&#93; Subsequently, this settlement was conquered by the [state of Yan](/State_of_Yan) and designated as its capital.&#160;&#91;44&#93;

#### Early Imperial China

<p style="text-align: center;">
  <a href="/Pagoda_of_Tianning_Temple_(Beijing)" title="Tianning Pagoda"><img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/Tianning_Pagoda.JPG/220px-Tianning_Pagoda.JPG" alt="Tianning Pagoda" width="220" height="293" decoding="async" loading="lazy"/></a>
  <br/>
  <small>The [Tianning Pagoda](/Pagoda_of_Tianning_Temple_(Beijing)), dating from the [Liao dynasty](/Liao_dynasty) around 1120.</small>
</p>

Following the unification of China by the [First Emperor](/Qin_Shi_Huang) in 221 BC, Jicheng transitioned into a [prefectural capital](/Zhou_(region)).&#160;&#91;45&#93; During the [Three Kingdoms period](/Three_Kingdoms_period), it changed hands between [Gongsun Zan](/Gongsun_Zan) and [Yuan Shao](/Yuan_Shao) before ultimately being captured by [Cao Cao](/Cao_Cao).&#160;In the AD 3rd century, during the [Western Jin](/Jin_dynasty_(265%E2%80%93420)), the town's status was reduced, with the prefectural seat relocated to the neighboring [Zhuozhou](/Zhuo_Prefecture).&#160;The [Sixteen Kingdoms](/Sixteen_Kingdoms) period, characterized by the conquest and division of northern China by the [Wu Hu](/Five_Barbarians), saw Jicheng briefly serve as the capital of the [Xianbei](/Xianbei) [Former Yan](/Former_Yan) Kingdom.&#160;&#91;46&#93;

After China was reunified by the [Sui dynasty](/Sui_dynasty) in 581, Jicheng, also known as [Zhuojun](/Zhuo_Commandery), became the northern terminus of the vital [Grand Canal](/Grand_Canal_(China)).&#160;Under the [Tang dynasty](/Tang_dynasty), Jicheng, referred to as [Youzhou](/Youzhou), functioned as a key military frontier command center.&#160;During the [An-Shi Rebellion](/An-Shi_Rebellion) and again amidst the political instability of the late Tang period, local military leaders established their own ephemeral Yan dynasties, renaming the city [Yanjing](/Yanjing), meaning "Yan Capital."&#160;It was during the Tang dynasty that the name Jicheng was superseded by Youzhou or Yanjing.&#160;In 938, following the collapse of the [Later Tang dynasty](/Later_Tang), the [Later Jin](/Later_Jin_(Five_Dynasties)) ceded the strategic [frontier territory including what is now Beijing](/Sixteen_Prefectures) to the [Khitan](/Khitan_people) Liao dynasty.&#160;The Liao considered the city their [Nanjing](/Liao_Nanjing), or "Southern Capital," one of four secondary capitals complementing their "Supreme Capital," Shangjing, located in present-day [Baarin Left Banner](/Baarin_Left_Banner) in [Inner Mongolia](/Inner_Mongolia).&#160;Some of the [oldest extant pagodas in Beijing](/List_of_pagodas_in_Beijing), including the [Tianning Pagoda](/Pagoda_of_Tianning_Temple_(Beijing)), date from this Liao period.

The Liao dynasty eventually fell to the [Jurchen Jin dynasty](/Jin_dynasty_(1115%E2%80%931234)) in 1122.&#160;The Jin initially ceded the city to the [Song dynasty](/Song_dynasty) before retaking it in 1125 during their [conquest of northern China](/Jin%E2%80%93Song_Wars).&#160;In 1153, the Jurchen Jin officially designated Beijing as their "Central Capital," or [Zhongdu](/Zhongdu).&#160;&#91;45&#93; The city faced a devastating siege by [Genghis Khan](/Genghis_Khan)'s invading [Mongolian army](/Mongol_Empire) in 1213, and was subsequently [razed to the ground](/Battle_of_Zhongdu) two years later.&#160;&#91;47&#93; Approximately two generations later, [Kublai Khan](/Kublai_Khan) initiated the construction of [Dadu](/Khanbaliq) (also known as Daidu to the Mongols, and more commonly as [Khanbaliq](/Khanbaliq)) to the northeast of the Zhongdu ruins, serving as the new capital for his [Yuan dynasty](/Yuan_dynasty).&#160;Construction spanned from 1264 to 1293,&#160;&#91;45&#93; &#91;47&#93; &#91;48&#93; significantly elevating the importance of this city on the northern periphery of [China proper](/China_proper).&#160;The city's layout was centered around the [Drum Tower](/Drum_Tower_and_Bell_Tower_of_Beijing), slightly north of modern Beijing, and extended from the present-day [Chang'an Avenue](/Chang%27an_Avenue) northward to what is now Line 10 of the [Beijing Subway](/Line_10,_Beijing_Subway).&#160;Remnants of the Yuan Dynasty's [rammed earth](/Rammed_earth) wall, known as the Tucheng, still stand today.&#160;&#91;49&#93;

#### Ming dynasty

<p style="text-align: center;">
  <a href="/Forbidden_City" title="Forbidden City"><img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/Forbidden_City_corner_tower_2008.jpg/320px-Forbidden_City_corner_tower_2008.jpg" alt="A corner tower of the Forbidden City, built by the Yongle Emperor during the early Ming dynasty" width="320" height="214" decoding="async" loading="lazy"/></a>
  <br/>
  <small>A corner tower of the [Forbidden City](/Forbidden_City), a creation of the [Yongle Emperor](/Yongle_Emperor) during the early [Ming dynasty](/Ming_dynasty).</small>
</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">
  <a href="/Overlapping_layout_of_Beijing" class="image"><img alt="Overlapping layout of Beijing during the Liao, Jin, Yuan and Ming dynasties" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/32/Overlapping_layout_of_Beijing_during_the_Liao%2C_Jin%2C_Yuan_and_Ming_dynasties.svg/320px-Overlapping_layout_of_Beijing_during_the_Liao%2C_Jin%2C_Yuan_and_Ming_dynasties.svg.png" width="320" height="263" decoding="async" loading="lazy"/></a>
  <br/>
  <small>Overlapping city layouts of Beijing across different dynasties.</small>
</p>

In 1368, shortly after the proclamation of the new [Hongwu era](/Hongwu_Emperor) of the [Ming dynasty](/Ming_dynasty), the [rebel](/Red_Turban_rebellion) leader [Zhu Yuanzhang](/Zhu_Yuanzhang) captured Dadu/Khanbaliq and ordered the Yuan palaces to be demolished.&#160;&#91;50&#93; As the [Yuan](/Northern_Yuan_dynasty) maintained control over [Shangdu](/Xanadu,_China) and [Mongolia](/Mongolia), Dadu was repurposed to supply Ming military garrisons in the vicinity and renamed Beiping, meaning "Northern Peace" in [Wade–Giles](/Wade%E2%80%93Giles) transliteration.&#160;&#91;51&#93; Under the Hongwu Emperor's feudal distribution of power, Beiping was granted to his son, [Zhu Di](/Zhu_Di), who was invested with the title "[Prince of Yan](/Prince_of_Yan)".

The premature death of [Zhu Yuanzhang](/Zhu_Yuanzhang)'s designated heir precipitated a [succession struggle](/Jingnan_Campaign) upon the emperor's demise. This conflict concluded with the victory of [Zhu Di](/Zhu_Di) and his ascension, marked by the declaration of the new [Yongle era](/Yongle_Emperor).&#160;Given his unfavorable treatment of the Ming capital, [Yingtian](/Nanjing) (modern [Nanjing](/Nanjing)), which had alienated many of its inhabitants, Zhu Di opted to establish his new capital in his former fiefdom.&#160;In 1403, the city of [Beiping](/Beiping) was officially renamed Beijing, signifying "Northern Capital," or [Shuntian](/Shuntian_Prefecture).&#160;&#91;36&#93; The construction of the magnificent new imperial residence, the [Forbidden City](/Forbidden_City), commenced in 1406 and was completed in 1420.&#160;&#91;47&#93; This era also saw the development of several other key landmarks that define the modern city, including the [Temple of Heaven](/Temple_of_Heaven) &#91;53&#93; and [Tian'anmen](/Tian%27anmen).&#160;On October 28, 1420, the same year the Forbidden City was finished, the city was formally declared the capital of the [Ming dynasty](/Ming_dynasty).&#160;&#91;54&#93; Beijing became the empire's primary capital, with Yingtian, also known as [Nanjing](/Nanjing) ("Southern Capital"), serving as a co-capital.&#160;(A decree issued in 1425 by Zhu Di's son, the [Hongxi Emperor](/Hongxi_Emperor), to reinstate Nanjing as the primary capital was never enacted; he died, likely from a heart attack, the following month.&#160;He was interred, like most subsequent Ming emperors, in an [elaborate necropolis](/Ming_tombs) situated to the north of Beijing.)

By the 15th century, Beijing had largely assumed its present-day configuration.&#160;The formidable [Ming city wall](/Beijing_city_fortifications) remained standing until modern times, when it was dismantled to make way for the construction of the [2nd Ring Road](/2nd_Ring_Road).&#160;&#91;55&#93; It is widely accepted that Beijing held the distinction of being the world's largest city for the majority of the 15th, 16th, 17th, and 18th centuries.&#160;&#91;56&#93; The [first documented church](/Christianity_in_China) was established by [Catholics](/Jesuit_China_Missions) in 1652 at the former site of [Matteo Ricci](/Matteo_Ricci)'s chapel; the present-day [Nantang Cathedral](/Cathedral_of_the_Immaculate_Conception_in_Beijing) was later erected on the same location.&#160;&#91;57&#93;

The city's Ming era concluded with its capture by [Li Zicheng](/Li_Zicheng)'s peasant army in 1644, which dissolved the dynasty.&#160;However, Li Zicheng and his [Shun court](/Shun_dynasty) abandoned the city without resistance when the [Manchu](/Manchu_people) forces led by Prince [Dorgon](/Dorgon) arrived just 40 days later.

#### Qing dynasty

<p style="text-align: center;">
  <a href="/Summer_Palace" title="Summer Palace"><img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/16/Summer_Palace_in_Beijing_2013.jpg/320px-Summer_Palace_in_Beijing_2013.jpg" alt="Summer Palace, one of several palatial gardens built by Qing emperors in the northwest suburb area" width="320" height="214" decoding="async" loading="lazy"/></a>
  <br/>
  <small>The [Summer Palace](/Summer_Palace), a notable example of the palatial gardens constructed by Qing emperors in the northwestern suburbs.</small>
</p>

[Dorgon](/Dorgon) subsequently established the [Qing dynasty](/Qing_dynasty), positioning it as the direct successor to the Ming (thereby delegitimizing [Li Zicheng](/Li_Zicheng) and his followers) &#91;58&#93; and reinstating Beijing as China's sole capital.&#160;&#91;59&#93; While the Qing emperors implemented some modifications to the Imperial residence, the fundamental Ming architectural structures and the city's overall layout largely remained intact.&#160;Facilities for Manchu religious practices were incorporated, yet the Qing also preserved traditional state rituals.&#160;Signage was often presented in both Chinese and Manchu, or solely in Chinese.&#160;This early Qing Beijing served as the backdrop for the renowned Chinese novel [Dream of the Red Chamber](/Dream_of_the_Red_Chamber).&#160;To the northwest of the city, Qing emperors commissioned the construction of several expansive palatial gardens, including the [Old Summer Palace](/Old_Summer_Palace) and the [Summer Palace](/Summer_Palace).

During the [Second Opium War](/Second_Opium_War), Anglo-French forces occupied the city's outskirts, engaging in looting and the destruction of the [Old Summer Palace](/Old_Summer_Palace) in 1860.&#160;The [Convention of Peking](/Convention_of_Peking) &#91;c&#93; concluded this conflict and, for the first time, granted Western powers the right to establish [permanent diplomatic presences](/Beijing_Legation_Quarter) within the city.&#160;From August 14 to 15, 1900, the [Battle of Peking](/Battle_of_Peking_(1900)) took place, an event that was part of the broader [Boxer Rebellion](/Boxer_Rebellion).
The subsequent attempt by the [Boxers](/Boxers_(group)) to expel foreign diplomatic missions and persecute [Chinese Christians](/Chinese_christian) led to the reoccupation of Beijing by eight [foreign powers](/Eight-Nation_Alliance).&#160;&#91;62&#93; During this period of conflict, several significant structures were destroyed, including the esteemed [Hanlin Academy](/Hanlin_Academy) and the (new) [Summer Palace](/Summer_Palace).
A [peace agreement](/Peace_agreement) was finalized on September 7, 1901, between the [Eight-Nation Alliance](/Eight-Nation_Alliance) and representatives of the Chinese government, [Li Hongzhang](/Li_Hongzhang) and [Yikuang](/Yikuang).&#160;The treaty stipulated a substantial indemnity of US$335 million (equivalent to over US$4 billion in contemporary currency), payable with interest over 39 years.&#160;Furthermore, it mandated the execution or exile of government officials who supported the Boxers and the demolition of Chinese fortifications and defensive structures throughout much of northern China.&#160;Ten days after the treaty's signing, the foreign armies withdrew from Beijing, although their legation guards remained stationed in the city until the outbreak of [World War II](/World_War_II).&#160;&#91;63&#93;

Following the treaty's ratification, [Empress Dowager Cixi](/Empress_Dowager_Cixi) returned to Beijing from her "inspection tour" on January 7, 1902.&#160;Although the Qing dynasty's rule over China was restored, it was significantly weakened by the repercussions of the Boxer Rebellion, the imposed indemnity, and the treaty's stringent conditions.&#160;&#91;64&#93; The Dowager passed away in 1908, and the dynasty ultimately collapsed in 1911.

#### Republic of China

<p style="text-align: center;">
  <a href="/Tiananmen" title="Tiananmen"><img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/85/Chiang_Kai-shek_portrait_at_Tiananmen.jpg/320px-Chiang_Kai-shek_portrait_at_Tiananmen.jpg" alt="A large portrait of Chiang Kai-shek was displayed above Tiananmen after World War II." width="320" height="213" decoding="async" loading="lazy"/></a>
  <br/>
  <small>A prominent portrait of [Chiang Kai-shek](/Chiang_Kai-shek) adorned [Tiananmen](/Tiananmen) following [World War II](/World_War_II).</small>
</p>

The architects of the [Xinhai Revolution](/Xinhai_Revolution) in 1911 aimed to supplant Qing rule with a republican system.&#160;Initially, leaders such as [Sun Yat-sen](/Sun_Yat-sen) intended to re-establish the capital in [Nanjing](/Nanjing).&#160;However, after the Qing general [Yuan Shikai](/Yuan_Shikai) successfully compelled the abdication of the last Qing emperor and secured the revolution's success, the revolutionaries appointed him as the president of the newly formed [Republic of China](/Republic_of_China_(1912%E2%80%931949)).&#160;Yuan maintained his capital in Beijing and swiftly consolidated his authority, even declaring himself emperor in 1915.&#160;His death less than a year later &#91;65&#93; resulted in China's fragmentation under the control of regional warlords.&#160;Following the successful [Northern Expedition](/Northern_Expedition_(1926%E2%80%931927)) conducted by the [Kuomintang](/Kuomintang), the capital was officially relocated to [Nanjing](/Nanjing) in 1928.&#160;On June 28 of that same year, Beijing's name was reverted to Beiping, rendered at the time as "Peiping".&#160;&#91;66&#93; &#91;67&#93;

On July 7, 1937, a confrontation erupted between the 29th Army and the Japanese forces in China at the [Marco Polo Bridge](/Marco_Polo_Bridge), situated near the [Wanping Fortress](/Wanping_Fortress) southwest of the city.&#160;This event, known as the [Marco Polo Bridge Incident](/Marco_Polo_Bridge_Incident), ignited the [Second Sino-Japanese War](/Second_Sino-Japanese_War), which is recognized in China as [World War II](/World_War_II).&#160;During the course of the war, &#91;66&#93; Beijing fell under Japanese control on July 29, 1937, &#91;68&#93; and became the seat of the [Provisional Government of the Republic of China](/Provisional_Government_of_the_Republic_of_China_(1937%E2%80%931940)), a [puppet state](/Puppet_state) that governed the ethnic Chinese territories occupied by Japan in [northern China](/North_China).&#160;&#91;69&#93; This provisional government was later absorbed into the larger [Wang Jingwei regime](/Reorganized_National_Government_of_China) based in Nanjing.&#160;&#91;70&#93;

#### People's Republic of China

<p style="text-align: center;">
  <a href="/Tiananmen" title="Tiananmen"><img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f4/Tiananmen_Square_at_night_with_flag.jpg/320px-Tiananmen_Square_at_night_with_flag.jpg" alt="Tiananmen during People&#39;s Republic of China" width="320" height="213" decoding="async" loading="lazy"/></a>
  <br/>
  <small>[Tiananmen](/Tiananmen) under the People's Republic of China.</small>
</p>

In the concluding stages of the [Chinese Civil War](/Chinese_Civil_War), the [People's Liberation Army](/People%27s_Liberation_Army) peacefully secured control of the city on January 31, 1949, as part of the [Pingjin Campaign](/Pingjin_Campaign).&#160;On October 1 of that year, [Mao Zedong](/Mao_Zedong) formally announced the establishment of the [People's Republic of China](/People%27s_Republic_of_China) from atop [Tiananmen](/Tiananmen).&#160;He reinstated the city's name to Beijing, designating it as the new capital.&#160;&#91;71&#93; This decision had been reached by the [Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference](/Chinese_People%27s_Political_Consultative_Conference) just a few days prior.

During the 1950s, the city began to expand beyond its historical walled core and surrounding neighborhoods.&#160;This expansion included the development of heavy industries in [the west](/Shijingshan_District) and the construction of residential areas in [the north](/Hepingli_Subdistrict,_Beijing).&#160;Significant portions of the [Beijing city wall](/Beijing_city_wall) were demolished in the 1960s to facilitate the construction of the [Beijing Subway](/Beijing_Subway) and the [2nd Ring Road](/2nd_Ring_Road).

The [Cultural Revolution](/Cultural_Revolution), spanning from 1966 to 1976, saw the genesis of the [Red Guard](/Red_Guard_(China)) movement in Beijing, and the city's government became an early target of purges.&#160;By the autumn of 1966, all city schools were closed, and over a million Red Guards converged on Beijing for eight major rallies held in Tiananmen Square with Mao.&#160;&#91;72&#93; In April 1976, a large public assembly of Beijing residents gathered in Tiananmen Square to protest against the [Gang of Four](/Gang_of_Four) and the Cultural Revolution.&#160;This demonstration was [forcefully suppressed](/1976_Tiananmen_incident).&#160;In October 1976, the Gang was apprehended in [Zhongnanhai], marking the end of the Cultural Revolution.&#160;Subsequently, in December 1978, the [Third Plenum of the 11th Party Congress](/Third_Plenary_Session_of_the_11th_CPC_Central_Committee) convened in Beijing under the leadership of [Deng Xiaoping](/Deng_Xiaoping).&#160;This plenum reversed the verdicts against victims of the Cultural Revolution and initiated the transformative ["policy of reform and opening up".](/Chinese_economic_reform)

Since the early 1980s, Beijing's urban footprint has expanded dramatically, marked by the completion of the 2nd Ring Road in 1981 and the subsequent addition of the [3rd](/3rd_Ring_Road_(Beijing)), [4th](/4th_Ring_Road), [5th](/5th_Ring_Road), and [6th](/6th_Ring_Road) ring roads.&#160;&#91;73&#93; &#91;74&#93; A 2005 newspaper report indicated that the newly developed Beijing was one-and-a-half times its previous size.&#160;&#91;75&#93; [Wangfujing](/Wangfujing) and [Xidan](/Xidan) have evolved into bustling commercial districts, &#91;76&#93; while [Zhongguancun](/Zhongguancun) has emerged as a major hub for electronics in China.&#160;&#91;77&#93; In recent years, this urban expansion has also brought to the forefront critical issues of urbanization, including [traffic congestion](/Traffic_congestion), [poor air quality](/Air_pollution), the loss of historic neighborhoods, and a substantial influx of migrant workers from less developed [rural areas](/Rural_area) of the country.&#160;&#91;78&#93; The city has also been the site of numerous pivotal events in recent Chinese history, most notably the [Tiananmen Square protests of 1989](/Tiananmen_Square_protests_of_1989).&#160;&#91;79&#93; Beijing has hosted major international sporting events, such as the [2008 Summer Olympics](/2008_Summer_Olympics), the [2015 World Athletics Championships](/2015_World_Athletics_Championships), and the [2022 Winter Olympics](/2022_Winter_Olympics), solidifying its status as the only city to have hosted both the [Winter](/Winter_Olympics) and [Summer Olympic Games](/Summer_Olympics).&#160;&#91;80&#93;

In terms of global connectivity, as of 2024, Beijing was categorized as an "Alpha+" city by the [Globalization and World Cities Research Network](/Globalization_and_World_Cities_Research_Network), placing it among the world's leading global cities.

### Geography

•
Main article: [Geography of Beijing](/Geography_of_Beijing)

Beijing is strategically situated at the northern edge of the expansive, roughly triangular [North China Plain](/North_China_Plain), which opens towards the south and east.&#160;The city and the agricultural heartland of northern China are protected from the encroaching desert steppes by mountains to the north, northwest, and west.&#160;The northwestern sector of the municipality, particularly the districts of [Yanqing District](/Yanqing_District) and [Huairou District](/Huairou_District), is dominated by the [Jundu Mountains](/Jundu_Mountains), while the western region is defined by Xishan, commonly known as the [Western Hills](/Western_Hills).&#160;The iconic [Great Wall of China](/Great_Wall_of_China), traversing the northern expanse of Beijing Municipality, was ingeniously constructed along the rugged topography to serve as a defense against nomadic incursions from the steppes.&#160; [Mount Dongling](/Mount_Ling_(Beijing)), located within the Western Hills and straddling the border with [Hebei](/Hebei), represents the highest point within the municipality, reaching an elevation of 2,303 meters (7,556 feet).

Several major rivers, including the [Chaobai](/Chaobai_River), [Yongding](/Yongding_River), and [Juma](/Juma_River_(China)), flow through the municipality, all forming tributaries within the [Hai River](/Hai_River) system and proceeding in a southeasterly direction.&#160;The Miyun Reservoir, situated on the upper reaches of the Chaobai River, stands as the largest reservoir within the municipality's boundaries.&#160;Beijing also marks the northern terminus of the historic [Grand Canal](/Grand_Canal_of_China), which extends to [Hangzhou](/Hangzhou) and was engineered over 1,400 years ago as a critical transportation artery.&#160;Additionally, the city is a key point in the [South–North Water Transfer Project](/South%E2%80%93North_Water_Transfer_Project), a modern engineering feat designed to channel water from the [Yangtze River](/Yangtze_River) basin.

The urban core of Beijing, located on the plains in the south-central part of the municipality at an elevation of 40 to 60 meters (130–200 feet), occupies a relatively small but expanding portion of the municipality's total area.&#160;The city's layout is characterized by its concentric organization around several [ring roads](/Ring_Roads_of_Beijing).&#160;The [Second Ring Road](/Second_Ring_Road_(Beijing)) precisely follows the path of the former [old city walls](/Beijing_city_wall), while the [Sixth Ring Road](/Sixth_Ring_Road) connects various satellite towns situated in the surrounding suburban areas.&#160;At the very heart of Beijing lies [Tian'anmen](/Tian%27anmen) and its expansive [Tian'anmen Square](/Tian%27anmen_Square), directly south of the imperial [Forbidden City](/Forbidden_City).&#160;To the west of [Tian'anmen](/Tiananmen) is [Zhongnanhai](/Zhongnanhai), the current seat of China's leadership.&#160; [Chang'an Avenue](/Chang%27an_Avenue), which bisects Tiananmen and the Square, serves as the city's primary east–west axis.

Beijing's pattern of urban development, radiating outwards from the historic inner city to its periphery, is often described with the idiom "spreading like a pancake" ( tan da bing ).&#160;&#91;82&#93; &#58;&#8202;135&#8202; This characteristic urban sprawl is frequently cited as a contributing factor to the city's persistent urban challenges.&#160;&#91;82&#93; &#58;&#8202;135&#8202;

### Climate

<p style="text-align: center;">
  <a href="/File:Beijing_average_monthly_temperature_and_precipitation.svg" title="Beijing average annual temperatures from 1970 to 2019 during summer (June, July, and August) and winter (December, January, and February). Weather station data from NOAA. For comparison, the Global Surface Temperature Anomaly rose by approximately one degree over the same time period."><img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d8/Beijing_average_monthly_temperature_and_precipitation.svg/320px-Beijing_average_monthly_temperature_and_precipitation.svg.png" alt="Beijing average annual temperatures from 1970 to 2019 during summer (June, July, and August) and winter (December, January, and February). Weather station data from NOAA. For comparison, the Global Surface Temperature Anomaly rose by approximately one degree over the same time period." width="320" height="226" decoding="async" loading="lazy"/></a>
  <br/>
  <small>Average monthly temperatures and precipitation in Beijing.</small>
</p>

Beijing experiences a monsoon-influenced [humid continental climate](/Humid_continental_climate) ([Köppen](/K%C3%B6ppen_climate_classification): Dwa ), with transitional zones bordering on a [cold semi-arid climate](/Cold_semi-arid_climate) ([Köppen](/K%C3%B6ppen_climate_classification): BSk ) in its southern and northwestern regions.&#160;The climate is characterized by hot, humid summers, driven by the East Asian [monsoon](/Monsoon), and brief, cold, dry winters, influenced by the vast [Siberian anticyclone](/Siberian_High).&#160;&#91;83&#93; Spring often brings sandstorms originating from the [Gobi Desert](/Gobi_Desert), sweeping across the [Mongolian steppe](/Mongolian-Manchurian_grassland), accompanied by rapid warming but generally dry conditions.&#160;Autumn, mirroring spring, is a transitional period with minimal rainfall.&#160;From 2001 to 2024, the warmest periods in Beijing typically occur in early August, while the coldest are observed in late January.&#160;According to China's standard seasonal divisions, Beijing transitions into spring on March 26, summer on May 20, autumn on September 13, and winter on October 31.&#160;In recent years, due to accelerated warming in March and September and slower warming in May and October, Beijing's autumn season tends to be shorter than its spring.&#160;The average annual temperature in Beijing's urban area hovers between 12.9 °C (55.2 °F) and 13.3 °C (55.9 °F).&#160;The average daily minimum temperature ranges from 7.7 °C (45.9 °F) to 8.4 °C (47.1 °F), and the average daily maximum temperature falls between 18.5 °C (65.3 °F) and 18.9 °C (66.0 °F).&#160;The monthly average daily temperature in January is −2.7 °C (27.1 °F), contrasting with July's average of 27.2 °C (81.0 °F).&#160;Annual precipitation averages approximately 528.0 mm (20.79 inches) (with Haidian and Chaoyang districts recording an average of 584.2 mm (23.00 inches)), with nearly three-quarters of this total falling between June and August.&#160;The city experiences around 2,490.5 hours of bright sunshine annually, with monthly possible sunshine percentages ranging from 42% in July to 62% in January and February.&#160;Extreme temperatures recorded since 1951 have ranged from a low of −27.4 °C (−17.3 °F) on February 22, 1966, to a high of 41.9 °C (107.4 °F) on July 24, 1999.&#160;&#91;84&#93; &#91;85&#93;

